					<marginalia_text>
						<!-- Continued from facing page, head, Ha2.201v --> [p. 226: Vultu, voce, gestu; omni parte absolutus vir:]
						idq[ue] Semper: et apud maximas maximè.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>[p. 226: In expression, voice, and gesture: in all parts the man is absolute:] and this he always is: and especially among the greatest.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="EN">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						( Both, neither: one, both. )
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						Somnium splendidum, sed miserum.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>A splendid, but miserable dream.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="270" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Ferdinandi Corduba[e] singulare in perdiscendis artibus Arcanum: vnicus artis
						vnus absolutus auctor: et Virtus sua ipsius semper vnita.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Gonzalo Fernández de Córdoba"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="270" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						Cum quotidiana /
						repetitione; et 
						acerrima collatione.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>The singular mystery of Gonzalo Fernández de Córdoba in learning arts thoroughly: the unique and one complete author of art: and his virtue was always united in itself.
				With daily repetition and the most keen union.
			</translation> 
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="270" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Ingenuitatis est, alioru[m] magna maximi a[e]stimare: tua maxima parui pendere.
						Simplicis iudicij nullu[m] certius argumentu[m], quàm paruis lucris, aut laudibus gloriari.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>It is a sign of noble-mindedness to estimate the great deeds of the greatest one of other men: to weigh your greatest things against the small. 
			It is a sign of a simple person to glorify no argument of judgement more certain than with small profits or by praises.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
